        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "A [z&sup3;](#z3){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"cubic zem\"} is 1 keg. A keg of water🌊weighs 64 [kilograms]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"thousands of grams\"}, 128 Dec pounds, or a 1000 Dec [kilograins]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"thousands of grains\"} ([kg](#kg){#kilograin .tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"kilograins\"}). If [Leonardo da Vinci](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonardo_da_Vinci#:~:text=an%20Italian%20polymath%20of%20the%20High%20Renaissance)'s [Vitruvian Man](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitruvian_Man#:~:text=a%20drawing%20by%20the%20Italian%20Renaissance%20artist%20and%20scientist%20Leonardo%20da%20Vinci) were 4 [z](#z){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"zems\"} tall, we could measure 1 [z](#z){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"zem\"} from his knees to his feet🦶or from his elbows💪to his fingertips. If he also weighed 1000 Dec [kg](#kg){#kilograin .tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"kilograins\"}, his [body mass index](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_mass_index#:~:text=the%20body%20mass%20divided%20by%20the%20square%20of%20the%20body%20height) ([bmi](#bmi){#bodymassindex .tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"body mass index\"}) would be 62.5 [kg](#kg){#kilograin .tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"kilograins\"} per [x](#x){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"hexamilliares\"} ($\\text {kg}\\over\\text x$) or 25 kilograms per [m&sup2;](#m2){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"square meters\"} ($\\text {kilogram}\\over\\text m^2$).\n",
        "\n",
        "# Body mass index (bmi) {.hiddenheading #sec-bmi}\n",
        "\n",
        "A normal [bmi](#bmi){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"body mass index\"} ranges from 46.25 to 62.5 $\\text {kg}\\over\\text x$ or 18.5 to 25 $\\text {kg}\\over\\text m^2$. A person with a [bmi](#bmi){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"body mass index\"} above 75 $\\text {kg}\\over\\text x$ or 30 $\\text {kg}\\over\\text m^2$ can be classified as obese. A [bmi](#bmi){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"body mass index\"} of \\${kgrains} [kg](#kg){#kilograin .tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"kilograins\"} &div; \\${zem2} [x](#x){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"hexamilliares\"} = \\${bmi} $\\text {kg}\\over\\text x$ = \\${kgrams} kilograms &div; \\${meter2} [m&sup2;](#m2){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"square meters\"} = ${bmim2} $\\text {kilograms}\\over\\text m^2$ is considered \\${bmiStr}.\n",
        "\n",
        "```{ojs}\n",
        "//| echo: false\n",
        "//| label: kginput\n",
        "viewof kilograins = Inputs.range([0, 10000], {label: \"Kilograins\", value: 1000, step: 1})\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "```{ojs}\n",
        "//| echo: false\n",
        "//| label: zinput\n",
        "viewof zems = Inputs.range([0, 10], {label: \"Zems\", value: 4, step: 0.01})\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "# Centizem centimeter inch {.hiddenheading #sec-cci}\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.column-page-right fig-align=\"left\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:.825rem;\"}\n",
        "![](../../asset/ruler1dz.svg){#ruler}\n",
        "[Wikimedia](https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Ruler_illustration.svg)\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "The longest length depicted in the image of a ruler📏above is 1 [dz](#dz){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"decizem\"}, 1 [nc](#nc){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"nanotaur\"}, 4 [centimeters]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"hundredths of a meter\"}, or $8\\over5$ Dec inches, and the shortest length is $1\\over2$ [mz](#mz){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"millizems\"}, $1\\over5$ [millimeters]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"thousandths of a meter\"}, $1\\over125$ Dec inches, or $1\\over127$ [US](#us){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"United States\"} customary inches. A [US](#us){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"United States\"} customary inch is $127\\over2$ [mz](#mz){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"millizems\"}, $127\\over5$ millimeters, or $127\\over125$ Dec inches. A Dec inch is $5\\over2$ centimeters. A centimeter is $5\\over2$ [cz](#cz){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"centizems\"}. A [z](#z){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"zem\"} is 4 decimeters. A decimeter is 4 Dec inches.\n",
        "\n",
        "# Claude Boniface Collignon {.hiddenheading #sec-cbc}\n",
        "\n",
        "In [1788]{.color788}, [Claude Boniface Collignon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claude_Boniface_Collignon#:~:text=a%20French%20attorney%20who%20contributed%20to%20scientific%20and%20social%20reforms%20in%20the%20time%20of%20the%20French%20Revolution) proposed measuring length in [dz](#dz){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"decizems\"} or [nc](#nc){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"nanotaurs\"} and tracking time in [deks](#dek){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"groups of ten days\"}, [dd]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"decidays\"}, [md](#md){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"millidays\"}, [µd](#ud){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"microdays\"}, and [nanodays]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"billionths of a day\"} ([nd](#nd){#nanoday .tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"nanodays\"})[^2]. On [[2025]{.color025}[+]{.mono}[039]{.colorD039}]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"April 9, 2025\"}, while searching for units similar to [c]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"taur\"} and [z]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"zem\"}, I noticed the definition of a [zem]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"zone equatorial meter\"}, 1 [z](#z){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"zem\"} = [10^-8^]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"a hundred millionth\"} [c](#c){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"taur\"} = 40 centimeters, in a table of [ten possible length units](https://www.roma1.infn.it/~dagos/history/sm/node12.html) from a [2004]{.color004} [arxiv](https://arxiv.org/abs/physics/0412078) [article](https://www.roma1.infn.it/~dagos/history/sm/sm.html) entitled \"Why does the meter beat the second?\"[^3].\n",
        "\n",
        "# Summary {.unnumbered #tldr}\n",
        "\n",
        "This article introduces the Dec measurement system and describes how Dec uses metric prefixes and the properties of the planet Earth🌍to define units based on turns for geographic coordinates, compass🧭directions, dates, times, speeds, distances, areas, volumes, and weights. Each unit has a unique name, such as [λ](#lambda){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"parallel\"}, [m](#m){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"meridian\"}, [r](#r){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"rose\"}, [y](#y){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"year\"}, [d](#d){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"day\"}, [b](#b){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"beat\"}, [v](#v){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"omegar\"}, [c](#c){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"taur\"}, [z](#z){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"zem\"}, or [x](#x){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"hexamilliare\"}.\n",
        "\n",
        "Dec attempts to bridge the gap, improve interoperability, and faciliate conversion between the [US](#us){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"United States\"} customary and [SI](#si){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"International System of Units\"} measurement systems by redefining [US](#us){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"United States\"} customary units. Redefinition of [US](#us){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"United States\"} customary units makes inches [~]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"approximately\"}[1.58%]{.color0158} shorter, miles [~]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"approximately\"}[0.58%]{.colorMile} shorter, pints [~]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"approximately\"}[5.67%]{.colorPint} larger, ounces [~]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"approximately\"}[8.21%]{.colorFlOz} larger, and pounds [~]{.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"approximately\"}[1.23%]{.colorMass} lighter.\n",
        "\n",
        "Dec color🎨labels🏷can convey an impression of a value at a glance. [Xet](#xet){.tool data-bs-toggle=\"tooltip\" data-bs-title=\"Tenet\"} sound🔊labels🏷allow us to estimate a value without even having to look at it. Both types of labels can help avoid confusion when [decimal separators](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_separator#:~:text=In%20English%2Dspeaking%20countries%2C%20the%20decimal%20point%20is%20usually%20a%20small%20dot%20%28.%29%20placed%20either%20on%20the%20baseline) appear, disappear, or move due to a measurement unit change such as the addition, removal, or replacement of a metric prefix.\n",
        "\n",
        "# Next {.unnumbered #next}\n",
        "\n",
        "Now that you have had a taste of Dec, I hope that you are hungry for more! If so, dive🤿deeper into Dec [dates](/dec/date) and [times](/dec/time) before tackling Dec [snaps](/dec/snap)🫰and [spans](/dec/span)🌈. My [filter](/quarto/filter), [include](/quarto/include), and [script](/quarto/script) articles discuss the [Quarto](/quarto) publishing system and how I display Dec [dates](/dec/date) in the [navigation bar](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Navigation_bar#:~:text=a%20section%20of%20a%20graphical%20user%20interface%20intended%20to%20aid%20visitors%20in%20accessing%20information), the [article list](/list), and [title blocks](https://quarto.org/docs/authoring/title-blocks.html) of my website.\n",
        "\n",
